text: I think people are overrating how groundbreaking this is. Is it a cool concept? Sure...but groundbreaking? I'm sure many film directors would preferably love it if they could use a time machine for films that have time gaps but its inconvenient. Its not that it can't be done or that people weren't sure that the resources were there to do it....its simply inconvenient, because you can tell the same exact story in a much shorter time while maintaining the same impact.  I feel like 'groundbreaking' achievements in films are reserved for films that have done something that people didn't know was possible and/or didn't think would be possible so soon. I can make a film that is 7 days long and takes place in real time, I wouldn't call that groundbreaking though.

text: I dislike the feel of this film for it lacks substance. Rather than being uniquely focused upon the true sentiments of a boy which derive from his development (boyhood) it presents a clichéd and rather stereotypical depiction of it. I say this because I do not let the trailer nor its music play me like a harp; but rather I watch it from an entirely objective viewpoint. I can't help but fell that this is an opportunity missed... a far better product would present the boy's unique struggles because although boyhood is a universal experience, it is uniquely experienced by the individual (the boy). Whilst, at the same time, having an appreciation of cultural/ historical contexts. This appears to be film solely founded on lazy, logical fallacies which permeate the consciousness of the western audience thats it material seems to appeal to.

text: Okay I may be in the vast minority in this one but I feel Boyhood is tremendously overrated. It's not, by any means, a bad film, just not nearly as good as most critics claim it is. The problem I have with this film is its glaring lack of substance. There is not a single character in this film that goes through some kind of character arc. The minor changes they undergo are left obscure and there are no hints as to what brought about those changes. None of the characters are likable. The entire film almost is a passive observation of this family's uneventful progression through the years. Although that worked very well in the first half of the movie the second half seemed superfluous. It brings back some of the most overused cliches (honestly if I had a nickel for every time a movie showed the divorced dad as cool and buff and the divorced mother as the complete opposite). The kid actors are great but as they age they seem less and less convincing. The dialogue as well suffers from cranky and mawkish moments. And on top of all that it lacks lacks a narrative structure. If you look at the Tree of Life, which is just as unstructured, Malick took advantage of that and turned it into a meditation on human behavior. Boyhood didn't even attempt to achieve anything of the sort. Tree of Life was poetry; Boyhood is just product. All the reviews I've read so far seem to be obsessed with the concept of the film rather than the final result. To me, Boyhood is yet another film that didn't come close to justifying its overblown hype. I would've given it a max of 7/10.

text: The only reason some people are skeptical about the movie or didn't like it as much is because of the reviews it got. I can bet that if you didn't even look at the reviews before you saw the movie, you'd appreciate it more. You can't really watch a movie like this and have any standards for it because it's never been done before. You guys probably went into the movie expecting some huge production with all these moments that'd be extra special but that's not what the movie was trying to go for. I can't really explain what the movie IS. It's just one of those movies where it doesn't need a hugely dramatic plot. Let me remind you that the movie was thought up in 2002, so if you see any themes that may have been in movies that came out since '02, obviously you're going to get some kind of cliche. It's expected, this movie was thought of in the early 2000s. Some people just didn't think about certain things before watching it, that's all. I loved the movie and I recommend it to anyone who can understand that this took 12 years to make and didn't get to start over from the beginning to modernize anything. Just try to understand what I'm saying, I'm probably not making any sense.

text: I just saw the movie. Its outstanding and very realistic. Men of all ages can relate to the boys life at some level, but that is where I found the film to be a little depressing. Although the film itself is a wonderful cinematic experience and in know way am I minimising how great it is, but I felt as though it taught me something profoundly obvious... it showed me that in a broad way every life is the same and that your life is just taking up insignificant space in the world. You are born, the you learn to walk, to run, to read and write. You go to kindergarden, middle school, highschool along the way you have girlfriends or boyfriends ( whatever your gender) then you go to college get a degree, get a job, marry someone, keep working throughout your life for no real purpose and then die.   Im sorry to be blunt but thats really what the movie made me think about... life is meaningless.

author: Pieter Van Berckel

text: I just saw this film. While I believe that the twelve year shoot was undeniably inventive and nostalgic, the film as a whole, and as a vehicle of plot, lacks a massive amount of impact. It feels like a senseless jumble of scenes from different years reassembled into an inorganic mass that begs to be coherent but lacks substance. The only factors that stand out are the directing and acting (Patricia delivered what can be called a good performance, but even the performances here are nothing that I would call Oscar-worthy). It seems to me that the span of filming is what has dragged critics to hail this film. I am not hating on it, but there are many other truly artful films this year with original premises that should be taken to consideration instead of this. Not forgetting performances by lead actresses that will be snubbed (I feel a stab of pain for Essie Davis and her masterful work in The Babadook). Those are my thoughts on the film. And it is with complete humbleness that I express my sadness towards the Academy and its injustices.  I hope others feel the same way too.

text: This movie is so amazing and literally gives me nostalgia. I was born and raised in Houston, so every scene of them growing up i feel like i can relate too. The family going to a Astros game, driving down downtown Houston, the fun plex bowling alley, running down the hill at the miller outdoor theatre... When they moved to San marcos i was so blown away by how much it related to me, since that's where i live now for college, and they literally filmed a scene down a street where I walk on everyday. The music they show in the movie is so on point in that time period. I am the same age as Mason, and went away to college this year and it got me in my feels so quick because I realize now how fast life is going by and all i have now are happy memories. I think this movie will always bring me back. Thanks Richard for this amazing amaaazing movie

text: I'm a fan of Richard Linklater's films. I really enjoyed the "Before" series of films , which told the story of two people , in three films made over a period of 18 years. With Boyhood he's done the same kind of thing but in one film filmed over a period of 12 years and it really works well. Linklater shows that you don't need bangs or crashes , CGI or ridiculous plots to make a good film . You just need to be a good story teller. I expect this to pick up many awards in the next month or two , simply because this kind of film making is quite rare and at 2 hours 45 minutes it might test some peoples patience but because i have two boys growing up and i'm already a fan of the director, i really liked it.  8 out of 10
author: redvalleyjohn

text: So many people on here saying how this film lacks conflict and has a boring storyline.. this film is not meant to be a thriller with explosions and huge plot twists that shock and keep you guessing. its a completely different style of film. this story is focused on the internal conflict which is going on as this boy grows and learns who he is. this is a film designed to inspie deep thought and open up concepts which the viewer can relate to in their own life (we dont seize the moment, the moment seizes us etc etc) and that is what makes this such a powerful film, its so real and so easy to relate to on so many different levels, it inspires thought and opens our eyes up to what life is meant to be. thats what makes this such a brilliant, unquestionably well made film

text: It's so absurd to me that there are all these comments about how this is such a stereotypical white American movie.  I have news for you - this movie was inspired by the director's real life experiences as a child and parent - and guess what?  He's a white American who grew up in Texas.  Would you rather he make a movie about the typical boyhood experience for a minority inner-city child?  By the way, this was already done in "Boyz in the hood" which happened to be a GREAT movie.  And I am a typical white American, who, although I couldn't relate to the experiences in that movie, completely appreciated it and was touched by it.  This was his life and this was his movie - another GREAT movie by the way.  Just get over it.

text: This is the best movie I've ever seen.  It's more than a movie.  Though I think in general you'd have to be at least 18 or older to "get it".  There is no plot, that's part of the point.  The lesson is emergent.  I think the mom hits at it a bit near the end.  The movie is two hours long, but took twelve years of what could be any random westerner's life.  In my opinion it's a narrative that is self-referential in its literalness and a not-so-gentle reminder that our time in life is fleeting.  Of course most teenagers watching the show think they are immortal so, this might be lost on them.  They might just watch the movie and think "this guy talks slowly" or "I don't like his jeans" or "she's prettier than me" or other small concerns.  And of course the closing statements sum up the point neatly, perhaps best enjoyed by any young person under the influence of psilocybin in the desert.

text: The movie was just "good."  Nothing dazzling- nothing academy award worthy.  The movie spanned through time... sooo?  We never knew why the mother chose drunks; what, specifically, caused her to separate with the father (he just seemed like a man-child).  If this was a coming of age story, why didn't we see any major confrontations between the son and mother/father (we all have them)?  If you want to see a GREAT movie about a boy growing up in a crappy home, see "This Boy's Life."  Great film-tremendous energy-great acting- and there's a true character arc of Leo's character.

text: I've been scrolling through the comments and noticing a lot of people giving the movie shit by saying its "dull" or "boring". Granted, some scenes of the movie aren't as upbeat as others, but that's what makes this story masterful. This film has made the greatest attempt at capturing the real feeling and presence of life itself through a fictional script and a camera. I can guarantee you that everyone's lives aren't as adventurous or spontaneous as most movies make them out to be. Some "moments" in our lives, the ones we love and cherish, may be awkward, they may be slow, they may be dull, they may be boring. But through it all, these moments add on to all of the fun, passionate, and wonderfully different memories that we love and cherish. You add them all together and you beautifully and accurately depict the essence of life, which, to me, is always not knowing what to expect...the good and the bad...

text: People slam this film lately for being nothing but a twelve year gimmick. But the truth is, it's so much more than that. People fail to see that Boyhood is beautifully written, superbly directed, wonderfully acted and stunningly shot from minute 1 through 165.   Every big, award winning film draws people who slate it left right and centre; it's inevitable. You can't please everyone.   But Boyhood is stunning, breath taking cinema. So simplistic in its complexity, and so wonderfully told. I loved it a lot.
author: MorrisMovies

text: I'm trying to understand the moral of this movie. Like for the other two really good movies this year, Birdman and Whiplash, had a point to the film. Birdman - What's popular and risk-adverse and financially secure isn't always something worthwhile and for Whiplash - In order to be great, you must sacrifice and persevere. For Boyhood though, it's seems more of a film-making experiment rather than the director actually carving out a story and having a point to the movie. If anything I thought the point of the movie was to show that in the end, you will never live up to your own expectations. But I am not sure if that is something I took from the movie or if it was the intention of the director.

text: I'm so glad this film didn't win "Best Picture."  A few comments written below point out the film was, in their view, a tribute to the "pointlessness" of life, "the importance of living in the moment," "one day just blurring into the next..." "nothing ever really too spectacular."  Bullshit!  Life is not pointless and humdrum- and if it is IT'S YOUR FAULT.  Those comments are written by people who don't take risks.... by people who stay at their humdrum job because it pays the rent and keeps their girlfriend or parents off their back, by people who never have a different opinion because it might rattle the herd, by people who stay with someone who never wants to get off the couch.  "Boyhood" failed because it didn't dare to go off the rails and reveal the deepest layers of how events shape our decisions about what kind of people we become.  EVERYTHING (except the theme song) about this film was neutral.  BORING and neutral.... a Showtime, harmless original.       A challenge the director to reply to this post.

text: This movie was utter bullshit. If it was not for the buzz and attention it had gotten for being filmed over 12 yrs, NO ONE would care for it. Especially no one would have watched it and pretended to like it, that is certain. You have two groups of viewers; *People who saw it for what it is (a gimmick) awfully done, lacking any real articulation/artistic expression... -- *And the fan-boys/girls who believe they are "deep" and artistic themselves, who will justify what crap it is by acting like the boring and pointlessness of it is the "intended" mark. If you want to watch a REAL movie, that did it right--with a similar storyline/plot, spanning over time for a young adult--watch This Boy's Life. It's a great coming-of-age film, following a young Leonardo Dicaprio. It portrays him as a young boy through young adult; his struggle dealing with an abusive father, in a dead-end small town.

text: This movie was soo boring and sloww. It's one of the worst I've seen, and I don't need a ton of action to keep me hooked. Im all about deep and meaningful messages but this had no message whatsoever to give, so I don't know why people are saying that if you don't like this film you pissed the point of it. It's pretentious to call this boring film an artistic masterpiece. If it is really supposed to reflect that life itself is pointless, I could have just seen some tumblr post dramatically saying "life is pointless," not watch 3 hours of a boring film that took 12 years to make. Life isn't even like this. Our lives are way more interesting than this and filled with ups and downs. In this film their lives looked pretty flat, so even if there is not any character or plot development because "it's real life," there should still be some fluctuation. The conversations were boring and the characters were boring. The end was boring and it was too long. The dad was an awesome character though I loved him. To be fair the beginning of this film was really good but halfway through when nothing was happening it started dragging and dragging.

text: I wasn't planning on commenting on this since the movie did come out a while ago, but given a lot of the comments in this section, I want to now. This is a movie about what it's like to be a boy growing up. It's a masterpiece of a coming-of-age film, filmed over 12 years, and details the major intervals of Mason's life as he goes through childhood and approaches adulthood. Is it boring? I suppose for some people it might be, but this film describes real life. There is nothing else like it in the film industry, which in my mind is tragic. If you want a spectacular, mind-blowing film, then this is not the one for you. But if you want to have a deep part of yourself to be touched and perhaps to leave the film a little misty-eyed, nostalgic, and reflective, then this film is right for you.

text: I watched this film yesterday and it hit me hard. Growing up I was always labelled as 'the quiet one' that 'never speaks' because I had huge amounts of social anxiety. I'm 17 now, and when I think back to what I did in my childhood it actually really depresses me. I've never had a real friend, I've never been in a relationship, I've always stuck to the rules, and I almost feel as if I've wasted my entire childhood. Watching this film made me feel like I've missed out on so much, and yes, they may be silly things, but I would still have liked to experience them. After watching Boyhood I feel a lot more inspired to take new risks in life, and most importantly - enjoy it! You can't change the past but you can shape your future. I'm going to university later this year and I'm nervous, but I'm also excited to see what it brings. This is the best film I've ever seen! :)

text: Acting was honest and genuine, the natural age progression concept is certainly compelling. What's most ironic about this movie is that it doesn't feel like a movie, because it doesn't include exaggerated or truly entertaining aspects to it. It just feels like an average life with no clear plotline. And while that is valuable and realistic, it just isn't... interesting. We already face reality on the daily. Why watch a 3 hour film to remind us what life is truly like, from a position where we can't even participate, when we live it every single day? Watch it if you want, but it'll be as pointless as it paints life as.

The only special thing that is happening is that his 2 stepfathers turn into rigor alcoholics. When his mom gets together with them they are both kind, smart and loving ... then time leap for 2 years and they are alcoholics that have nothing other to do than drink and be mean to the kids, especially to the boy of course. The problem is this movie shows a indeed superb mom and 3 Dads that either were assholes, or turn into assholes, without even giving us a hint why. The movie told some lessons that were really great, but the story itself seems just to tell: Dads are shit. Dont ask why, because its just the way it goes and you cant prevent it anyway.

text: I can hardly articulate the impact this movie made on me. It reminded me how much of a miracle it is to be alive. Helped me realize that the small moments in life, are beautiful, and many times you don't realize that until they are in the past. Yes, I was bored at parts of the movie, but that's part of the point! Life is not always interesting, yet those moments that are now in the past, they ARE something special, and helped us grow in some way.

text: Escolhei assistir esse filme por acaso agora em 26/04/2020, não tinha visto a sinopse nem a duração do filme 02: 42: 01, nem ao menos sabia que ele começou a ser gravado no ano de 2002 e terminou em 2013. Gostei bastante. Comecei pesquisar mais sobre o sobre a produção do filme e o diretor Richard Linklater não queria usar maquiagem para envelhecer os atores ou mesmo trocá-los durante a filmagem, por isso, ele manteve o mesmo elenco e gravou o filme durante 12 anos. Eu estava assistindo o filme por partes, assisti uns 30 minutos ai depois mais um pouco e tal, quando eu comecei a perceber e os atores estavam envelhecendo e eram as mesmas pessoas, resolvi pesquisar, mais sobre o filme. Estou assistindo agora pela segunda vez com mais atenção, pois não acompanhei direito na primeira vez, gostei da história..👍👍👍👍 Como tudo na vida, tem gente que não vai gostar, mas acredito que a maioria vai curtir demais a evolução e o crescimento do Ellar Coltrane Kinney Salmon. Deve ser muito loco ver seu crescimento em um filme, poucas pessoas experimentaram isso na vida, porque deve ter dado um trabalhão manter os mesmos atores durante todo o filme, bem legal.
